         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0000506">
               <p><persName>Sarah</persName> (maiden name unknown) was born in <placeName>Leeds,
                     Yorkshire</placeName>. She inclined toward Calvinism as a young woman but
                  joined the Methodists after hearing <persName>JW</persName> preach. She moved to
                     <placeName>London</placeName> in <date when="1757">1757</date> after her
                  husband deserted her, and boarded with <persName>Mary (Gardiner)
                  Clarke</persName>. Here she met <persName>Mary Bosanquet</persName>, which was the
                  beginning of a long friendship and shared ministry, in <placeName>Leytonstone,
                     Essex</placeName>, and then in <placeName>Morley, Yorkshire</placeName>. Both
                  women became prominent female preachers among <persName>JW</persName>&apos;s
                  followers, with <persName>Crosby</persName> pioneering the way. See
                     <persName>Frank Baker</persName>, &apos;<persName>John Wesley</persName> and
                     <persName>Sarah Crosby</persName>&apos;, <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 27 (<date
                     when="1949">1949</date>): 76–82; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 273; <hi
                     rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; Taft, <hi rend="italic">Holy Women</hi>, 2:23–115; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 83.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
